# Carpals

> The carpals are **8 short bones** arranged in 2 rows forming the wrist. They create the carpal tunnel on their palmar surface.

## 🔗 Connected Structures
- [[Radius]] — **Radiocarpal joint** — primary wrist joint
- [[Ulna]] — Indirect via the triangular fibrocartilage complex (TFCC)
- [[Metacarpals]] — **Carpometacarpal joints (CMC joints)**

## 🗂️ The 8 Carpal Bones

### Proximal Row (radial → ulnar)
| Bone | Feature |
|------|---------|
| Scaphoid | Largest; poor blood supply → AVN risk |
| Lunate | Crescent-shaped |
| Triquetrum | Ulnar side |
| Pisiform | Sesamoid bone; flexor carpi ulnaris attachment |

### Distal Row (radial → ulnar)
| Bone | Feature |
|------|---------|
| Trapezium | Saddle joint with 1st metacarpal |
| Trapezoid | Smallest carpal |
| Capitate | Largest carpal; central position |
| Hamate | Hook of hamate (Hamulus) |

**Mnemonic**: **"She Looks Too Pretty, Try To Catch Her"**

## 🔑 Carpal Tunnel
- **Floor**: Carpal bones (concave palmar surface)
- **Roof**: Flexor retinaculum
- **Contents**: FDS (×4), FDP (×4), FPL (×1), **median nerve** — 10 structures total

## 🏥 Clinical Significance
- **Scaphoid fracture** — Most common carpal fracture (70%); AVN risk due to poor blood supply
- **Carpal tunnel syndrome (CTS)** — Median nerve compression; thumb–middle finger numbness; thenar atrophy
- **Lunate dislocation** — Compresses carpal tunnel → acute CTS
- **TFCC injury** — Ulnar-sided wrist pain

